    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Please send me little book of <hi rend="underline">Litmus Paper</hi>. &amp; Bottle of Gum with brush, such as I have often had before</p>
<p>C. Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">Down, May 11<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The correspondent is conjectured from the fact that Baxter was CD’s usual chemist, and he supplied chemicals for CD’s work on <hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi>. The year is established by a note accompanying this letter in which <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1226.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Horace Darwin</ref> is said to have attested that the letter had to do with CD’s work on <hi rend="italic">Drosera</hi> (sundew). CD did experiments on <hi rend="italic">Drosera</hi> with litmus paper and bought some from ‘a druggist’ in 1873 (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 21, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9090A.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Edward Frankland, 7 October [1873]</ref>). He started to use the more sensitive litmus paper provided by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1739.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Frankland</ref> from October 1873 (see <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9094.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Edward Frankland, 10 October 1873</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
